'''Jean-Godefroy Bidima''' (born 1958 in [[Mfoumassi]]) is a Cameroonian philosopher, currently living in the United States.  Bidima is the former director of the program at the International College of Philosophy in Paris and as of 2015 is a professor in French and Italian and Yvonne Arnoult Chair in Francophone Studies at [[Tulane University]] in [[New Orleans]]. His fields of interest are cited as " Continental philosophy, literatures and arts of the Francophone world, African philosophies, juridical anthropology and medical ethics".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tulane.edu/liberal-arts/french-italian/faculty.cfm|title=Jean-Godefroy Bidima|publisher=Tulane University|accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref> He is the author of numerous books and articles on African philosophy, including ''Histoire et traversée : philosophie, politique et l’imaginaire en Afrique'', ''Philosophie negro-africaine'' (1995) and ''La palabre: une juridiction de la parole'' (1997).<ref name="Bidima1997">{{cite book|last=Bidima|first=Jean-Godefroy|title=La palabre: une juridiction de la parole|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MPa1AAAAIAAJ|date=1 January 1997|publisher=Michalon|isbn=978-2-84186-065-4}}</ref>

