'''Marcel Paquet''' (21 February 1947 &ndash; 22 November 2014) was a [[Belgium|Belgian]] [[philosopher]].
The most important influences on his thought were [[Spinoza]], [[Kant]], [[Hegel]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pharefm.be/agenda-id-1453.html|title=Agenda - Conférence  : Spinoza, Philosophe hollandais|website=www.pharefm.be}}</ref> [[Nietzsche]],<ref>Gerald Alvoet, ''Nietzsche et l'Europe: "Nous autres, bons Européens"'', ed. L'Harmattan, 2006, {{p.|100}}, {{ISBN|2296019285}}</ref><ref>Bellefroid et al, ''Joaquim Vital - esquisses pour un portrait'', éditions de la Différence, 2011, {{p.|96}}, {{ISBN|978-2729119256}}</ref> [[Heidegger]] and [[Michel Foucault]].<ref>''Politique de théâtre, morale sartrienne et gracieuse dialectique'', ''Nous autres Européens'', ''op.cit.''</ref>

Paquet rejected all forms of [[Idealism]] in favor of the sensory world. Insofar as he considered human beings to be no more than fragments of [[nature]], thought was considered by him to be the result of cerebral processes which operate largely beneath the level of consciousness. He insisted on the pre-eminence of the body and the fact that, for this reasons, consciousness observes the results of thought, but does not bring them into being.

Inspired by Nietzsche's notion of [[Eternal return#Friedrich Nietzsche|Eternal Recurrence]] - which Paquet treated not as a doctrine but an operational principle, that is as a means of disentangling ourselves from secondary aspects of our identity (determined by cultural, religious and moral factors) in order to recover our primary nature - he considered a return to the body as the sole ethical value.<ref>''Platon, l’éternel retour de la liberté'', ''op.cit.''</ref>

He developed this [[Spinoza]]n theme in a number of different directions: [[ontology]] (''L'enjeu de la philosophie'', ''Platon: l’éternel retour de la liberté''), [[political philosophy]] (''Nous autres Européens'', ''Le Fascisme Blanc'') and [[esthetics]], the latter in particular in relation to [[painting]] which he defined as the art of rendering the sensory visible.<ref>''Rouge Absolu'', op.cit.</ref> He is the author of a large number of essays consecrated to visual artists whom he knew personally: [[Jean Dubuffet]], [[Alexander Calder]], [[André Masson]], René [[Magritte]], [[Paul Delvaux]], [[Fernando Botero]], Sophia Vari, [[Guillaume Cornelis van Beverloo|Corneille]] (one of the six founders of the [[Cobra (avant-garde movement)|Cobra movement]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dbnl.org/tekst/_ons003198901_01/_ons003198901_01_0129.php|title=Ons Erfdeel. Jaargang 32 · dbnl|first=|last=DBNL|website=DBNL}}</ref> Bram Bogart, Anna Wilczynska-Wilska, Amann...

He is also the author of several philosophical novels, namely : ''Renaissance sécondaire'', ''Merde à Jésus'', ''L’affaire Socrate'', ''Marie et les Jean''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ladifference.fr/+-paquet-+.html?index=1&titre=P |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-01-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201230400/http://www.ladifference.fr/+-paquet-+.html?index=1&titre=P |archivedate=2014-02-01 |df= }}</ref>

He died in [[Poznań]], [[Poland]] on 22 November 2014.<ref>http://www.wspomnijbliskich.pl/39672362-nekrologi-marcel-paquet{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>http://www.ladifference.fr/LETTRE-DECEMBRE-2014-IN-MEMORIAM.html#lettre3467 {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213092848/http://www.ladifference.fr/LETTRE-DECEMBRE-2014-IN-MEMORIAM.html |date=2014-12-13 }}</ref>

== Life ==
Paquet was born in Jumet, near [[Charleroi]].   According to his own account, he had an unhappy childhood. He sought refuge in books, and in particular in Spinoza's [[Ethics (Spinoza)|Ethics]] and in Nietzsche's [[The Antichrist (book)|Antichrist]]. A school trip to [[London]] allowed him to discover the works of [[J. M. W. Turner|William Turner]]; later a visit to [[Amsterdam]] gave rise to his passion for the works of [[Rembrandt]] and [[Van Gogh]] as well as allowing him to meet the [[Situationist International|situationist]] painter and architect [[Constant Nieuwenhuys|Constant]], whose work ''Het Opstand van de Homo ludens'' ("''The uprising of'' [[Homo Ludens (book)|Homo Ludens]]") he translated into French.

He matriculated at the [[Université libre de Bruxelles|Free University of Brussels]] in 1964 and in 1967 became assistant to Professor Pierre Verstraeten. His graduation dissertation dealt with the problem of unity in [[Kant]]'s thought in the [[Critique of Judgment]] (''L’unité problématique du kantisme dans la Critique de la force de juger'').

In 1971, he became a junior associate ("''aspirant''") at the Belgian [[Fonds National de la Recherche Scientifique|National Fund for Scientific Research]].

He did research into [[fanaticism]] and published a number of articles including "Essai sur l’absolu" (''Essay on the concept of the Absolute'') which brought him to the attention of French philosopher Gérard Lebrun<ref>G. Lebrun, ''L'envers de la dialectique - Hegel à la lumière de Nietzsche'', éd. du Seuil, Paris, 2004, {{p.|64}}</ref> and led to a professorship in the history of German Philosophy at the University of Tunis.

It was during his period in Tunis, which lasted from 1972 to 1974, that he wrote his first published work ''L’enjeu de la philosophie'' ("The Question of Philosophy") and he began work on his doctoral dissertation on "The difference between the thought of Kant and Hegel on the question of the essence of art" (''La différence des pensées de Kant et de Hegel dans la question de l’essence de l’art''.<ref>''Botero, Essai d’analyse philosophique'', ''op.cit.'', {{p.|129}} ff.</ref>

In 1975, he was one of the founders of the publishing house ''Les Éditions de la Différence''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ladifference.fr/IMG/pdf/catalogue_mars2011.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-11-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201230320/http://www.ladifference.fr/IMG/pdf/catalogue_mars2011.pdf |archivedate=2014-02-01 |df= }}</ref>

In 1978, he obtained his doctorate and continued to work on issues related to painting (René [[Magritte]],<ref>Clara Elizabeth Orban, ed., ''The Culture of Fragments: Word and Images in Futurism and Surrealism'', Ed. Rodopi, Amsterdam, 1997, {{p.|125}}, {{ISBN|90-420-0111-9}}</ref> [[Paul Delvaux]], [[Fernando Botero]]).

In 1981, he took part, together with [[Hans-Georg Gadamer]] in the colloquium "1881: The great year of Zarathustra" organised at the [[Brock University]] of [[St. Catharines|Saint-Catharines]] in [[Canada]]:<ref>M. Paquet, "Nietzsche et l’art moderne", in ''The great year of Zarathoustra (1881-1981)'' ; edited by David Goicoechea, University press of America, 1983.</ref> he made a presentation of his concept of "''dansité''", a play on words which suggests both "innerness" and dance, which was later incorporated into his book ''Magritte ou l’éclipse de l’être''.<ref>''op.cit.''</ref>

He subsequently took up residence in [[Canada]], where he lived in [[Ontario]] and for a time in [[Quebec]].

In 1988, he taught [[French literature]] at the University of [[Udine]] in [[Italy]].

Upon his return to [[Belgium]], he made the acquaintance of Bram Bogart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bram-bogart.com/FR/home.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-11-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202164238/http://bram-bogart.com/FR/home.htm |archivedate=2014-02-02 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whitfordfineart.com/artist/biography/3461/bram_bogart |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-09-20 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304071411/http://www.whitfordfineart.com/artist/biography/3461/bram_bogart |archivedate=2016-03-04 |df= }}</ref> in relation to whom he wrote a number of articles.

In Paris in 1990 he met a number of artists of the "[[New New Painters|New New Painting]]" group and developed a theoretical account of their artistic approach, set out in a work published by the publishing house ''Nouvelles éditions françaises''.<ref>''New New Painting'', Nouvelles éditions françaises, Paris, 1992</ref>

In 1993, he created the "''École européenne de philosophie de Charleroi''". This school organized amongst other things courses on the concept of "ethical conciliation" and on a draft political constitution for [[Wallonia]] which Paquet drew up.<ref>http://archives.lesoir.be/charleroi-richard-miller-ouvre-le-cycle-de-l-ulb-une-no_t-20010530-Z0KHX5.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.lesoir.be/l-ulb-parraine-l-ecole-de-philosophie-de-marcel-paquet-_t-19940527-Z083HN.html|title=L'ULB PARRAINE L'ECOLE DE PHILOSOPHIE DE MARCEL PAQUET, COGITATIONS AU CHATEAU DE MONCEAU - Le Soir|website=lesoir.be}}</ref>

In 1996, he took up residence in [[Biarritz]]<ref>''Botero, Essai d’analyse philosophique'', ''op.cit'', {{p.|142-154}}</ref> where in 1997 he married the painter Anna Wilczynska-Wilska.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sudouest.fr/2012/05/17/l-artiste-peintre-anna-wilska-exposera-en-chine-717418-727.php|title=L’artiste peintre Anna Wilska exposera en Chine|website=SudOuest.fr}}</ref> He organized a retrospective dedicated to Bram Bogart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberation.fr/culture/1999/05/08/arts-biarritz-consacre-une-retrospective-a-l-artiste-hollandais-porte-sur-l-analite-biarrot-bogart-r_272366|title=Biarritz consacre une rétrospective à l'artiste hollandais porté sur l'analité. Biarrot Bogart. Rétrospective Bram Bogart, Jusqu'au 16 mai à l'espace muséal Bellevue|last=|first=|date=|website=liberation.fr|access-date=}}</ref> and various events devoted to the painter Amann and the pictorial movement of "New Pigmentation".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.secondemodernite.com/cms.php?id_cms=13|title=Biographie hermann amann - Seconde Modernité|website=www.secondemodernite.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sudouest.fr/2012/05/25/en-perpetuelle-quete-de-l-energie-du-rouge-724732-4037.php|title=En perpétuelle quête de l’énergie du rouge|website=SudOuest.fr}}</ref>

