{{Infobox recurring event | name = Philosophy Now Festival | native_name = | native_name_lang = | logo = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = | logo_size = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | status = <!-- e.g. defunct, active, inactive ... --> | genre = Philosophy festival | date = | begins = <!-- {{start date|YYYY|mm|dd}} --> | ends = <!-- {{end date|YYYY|mm|dd}} --> | frequency = Every two years | venue = | location = London | coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|type:event|display=inline,title}} --> | country = United Kingdom | years_active = <!-- {{age|YYYY|mm|dd}} Date of the first occurrence --> | first = 2011 | founder_name = | last = <!-- Date of most recent event; if the event will not be held again, use {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | prev = | next = | participants = | attendance = | capacity = | area = | budget = | activity = | leader_name = | patron = | organised = <!-- "organized=" also works --> | filing = | people = | member = | sponsor = Philosophy Now magazine | website = https://philosophynow.org/festival | footnotes = }}
The '''Philosophy Now Festival''' is a large philosophy festival held every two years in central London.
The Festival is hosted and organised by the newsstand magazine [[Philosophy Now]], which aims to take philosophy to the widest possible audience. The Festival is open to the general public, at little or no cost.
The first Philosophy Now Festival was held in 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://now-here-this.timeout.com/2011/12/17/philosophy-now-festival/|title=I Think, Therefore I Am Attending the Philosophy Now Festival|work=Time Out|date=17 December 2011|location=London}}</ref> It was held partly to mark the 20th anniversary of the launch of [[Philosophy Now]] magazine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://philosophynow.org/issues/89/The_Philosophy_Now_Festival|title=The Philosophy Now Festival|work=Philosophy Now|date=March 2012|location=London}}</ref> Since then the Philosophy Now Festival has become a regular biannual event. The second ''Philosophy Now'' Festival was held in 2013,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Philosophy Now Festival 2013 {{!}} Philosophy Now|url=https://philosophynow.org/festival/2013|website=philosophynow.org|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref> the third in 2015 and the fourth in January 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Philosophy Now Festival 2018 {{!}} Philosophy Now|url=https://philosophynow.org/issues/125/The_Philosophy_Now_Festival_2018|website=philosophynow.org|accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref> Each festival was a one-day event involving contributions from more than a dozen philosophy organisations including [[Philosophy For All]] and the [[Royal Institute of Philosophy]].
== Venue == The Festival is held at [[Conway Hall]], a large art deco building in [[Bloomsbury]] in central London.<ref>"Philosophy Now Festival" [http://philevents.org/event/show/1016 PhilEvents] Retrieved 15 August 2014.</ref> The Festival uses the entire building, and there are usually three or four events running at any one time.
== Against Stupidity Award == A regular feature of the Philosophy Now Festival is the presentation of the ''Philosophy Now'' Award for Contributions in the Fight Against Stupidity.<ref name="PNaward">{{Cite web|url=http://philosophynow.org/award|title=Philosophy Now Award for Contributions in the Fight Against Stupidity|access-date=5 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/8958079/The-worlds-biggest-problem-is-stupidity.html |title=The World's Biggest Problem is Stupidity |work=Daily Telegraph |date=15 December 2011 |location=London}}</ref> This always includes an acceptance speech, sometimes made via a video link.
Before the 2015 Philosophy Now Festival it was announced that the Award would for the first time be given to a children's author, [[Cressida Cowell]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/oct/22/cressida-cowell-how-to-train-your-dragon-philosophy-now-award-fight-against-stupidity|title=Children's author Cressida Cowell scoops philosophers' award for fight against stupidity|work=The Guardian|date=22 October 2015 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/books/authors/cressida-cowell-wins-award-for-combating-stupidity/|title=Cressida Cowell wins award for 'combating stupidity'|work=Daily Telegraph|date=22 October 2015|location=London}}</ref>
